Privacy at the ABC
Cookies and Other Technologies
FAQs in this section
Cookies and Other Technologies
What are cookies?
How does the ABC use cookies?
What digital technologies does the ABC use?
How can I control and delete cookies using my browser?
Does the ABC allow third parties to use these technologies on its digital services?
If you have read the
ABC Privacy Policy
, you may have come across some terms you did not understand. We have provided additional details about these terms below.
API
API stands for Application Programming Interface. It refers to a type of software that is used to help two different websites or apps communicate with each other.
Beacons
A “beacon” is a signal sent from your computer or device to a server on the Internet. Websites, apps and emails use software that reads cookies, local storage and other information stored on your computer or device and sends beacons to record that information.
This may include information about your user activity, including behavioural data such as your viewing history, location data such as your IP address, as well as information about your personalised settings and preferences.
Browser information
Browser information refers to some specific information about the web browser you are using when you contact the ABC. We may collect this information to help us understand and serve the browser technology our audiences are using, and to ensure that our Audience Support team can provide troubleshooting tips. This information may include the name and version of the browser you use when you contact us.
Cookies
A cookie is a small text file saved in your internet browser (Chrome, Firefox, Safari) or device (smartphone, tablet) each time you visit an ABC website or mobile app. They are used to identify your browser and/or device.
For more information about how the ABC uses cookies, read the FAQ,
How does the ABC use cookies?
Device identifiers
A device identifier is a string of letters that uniquely identifies your device or the browser on your device. This information is used to identify your device or the browser on your device on return visits and can be used to follow your user activity over time and remember things such as your personalised settings and preferences.
Event ID
Every action on an ABC website or app, like playing a video on ABC iview, or clicking a link on an ABC website, is known as an Event. Each event has an Event ID, which helps us measure and improve ABC websites and apps, as well as provide personalisation services such as remembering where you left off on a program.
Hashing
Hashing is a way for two parties to confirm they have the same information without sharing the information. For example, it turns your email address from something like this, big.ted@abc.net.au, to something like this, ‘f3dc567c84efb0634a65e7hg4b’, which is called a token. The token is then shared with our third-party partners to show you relevant ABC promotions on their platforms, and to measure and improve ABC promotional campaigns.
IP address
An IP address, or Internet Protocol address, is a series of numbers that identifies any device on a network. Computers use IP addresses to communicate with each other both over the internet as well as on other networks, such as the WiFi network in your home.
Local Storage
Local storage is a location within your web browser that websites and apps use to store files. These files are used to provide services such as saving your log in information or providing you with personalisation features.
Learn more about how the ABC uses these technologies by visiting our section on
Cookies and Other Technologies
, and reading the
ABC Privacy Policy
.
